Undercover‚Äôs autumn winter 2002 collection ‚Äúwitch‚Äôs cell division‚Äù is shaped by classic pop-culture witch imagery and robots. The two subcultures make an unlikely but fun-loving pair in this collection, blending a darker color pallet with the whimsical imagery of robots. Transformer‚Äôs being one of the clear influences for the collection, incorporates the mutable aspects of these robots in each piece by adding unconventional fabrics to familiar silhouettes giving them a transmutable shape. This black shirt features white crosses in a cross shape. Jun made these from blanks making them incredibly rare. Only one other has been sold on the market.

description:
SEXSCABS.COM
The Undercover Spring/Summer 2003 "Scab" collection was undoubtedly Jun Takahashi's most important collection, it set the stage & marked a turning point in his career. He took the opportunity of showcasing the true extent of his abilities to the world, at his debut collection at Paris in October 2002. It set the tone for the designers career, attaining praise from the likes of Rei Kawakubo stating on Jun Takahashi "The only one with courage."
The various references to the "Crust Punk" Aesthetic & Ethnic fabrics used created a tense atmosphere in the showroom. With subtle references to 9/11 during a tense time Jun Takahashi stepped in a realm which no designer at the time had even wanted to think about. He closed the show dressing models in a array of multi coloured burqas. In which shocked the crowd in a way nobody had expected, helping the collection & designer reach new levels of credit & praise from both media & consumers.

description: For sale is a vibrant Autumn Winter 2001 Undercover ‚ÄúGFY‚Äù utility belt bag. Originally inspired by the tactical holster belts worn by American police in the 1990‚Äôs, Jun Takahashi‚Äôs reinterpretation of this practical bag is a perfect example of how functionality can be seamlessly fused with fashion. Coming in a crisp grey and neon green colour-way, the bag features seven storage pockets of varying sizes, each brought together by an adjustable belt strap. All of these compartments are accented with a lightning bolt and crossbones motif, exclusively utilized on pieces from the early 2000‚Äôs. description:
Killer suit pants from Undercover's JohnUndercover line!
The detailing on this piece is typical of Undercover's unique lens towards any garment - studding detailing along the pockets, a button cuff hem, and a wool gabardine panel at the bottom back of each leg to contrast with the fine flannel wool suiting fabric that makes up the majority the garment. And what's great is that they are partially lined (as shown in the second to last image).
In terms of fit, these are meant to fit as a slight mid-rise in keeping with how most Undercover bottoms fit. They're a marked size 2, so I would say they fit a 29"-30" waist. They are slightly cropped, but considering where they are supposed to sit on the waist they sit at or slightly above the ankle (I've included the lookbook image to show how they would fit - for reference I normally wear a 32" full-length inseam and these fit me about the same as in the lookbook image).

description:
One of the most spectacular pieces of Jun‚Äôs career, this parka comes from the iconic AW06 ‚ÄúGuru Guru‚Äù collection and was shown in one of the Jun‚Äôs most iconic looks of all time, with a matching wrap scarf tied around the arms of the model. This piece is insane, comprised of a luxurious wool blend with a pilled effect to evoke real wear. It features a fur-lined hood with inserted wires which can be bent to alter the shape of the hood, a removable lining for multi-season wear, and a draped scarf attached at the neck which can be left to dangle downwards as it was on the runway or wrapped around the hood and clasped at the neck. It has an asymmetric wrap closure with two zippers and faux-shearling lined sleeves for an extra comfortable feel. Truly a magnificent piece, one which I am hoping will find a good home.
